## The Mechanics of Page Moves  
### Behind the Scenes  
A **[page move](/Page_move)** on Wikipedia isn’t merely renaming a page; it’s an act of controlled demolition and reconstruction. Editors with sufficient privileges can relocate a page, but the *redirect* is the safety net ensuring:  
- **Internal links** from other Wikipedia articles don’t dissolve into **[dead links](/Dead_link)**.  
- **External references** (from blogs, books, or desperate students citing Wikipedia at 3 AM) retain their fragile connection to human knowledge.  

### The Cost of Deletion  
Deleting this redirect would fracture **[link integrity](/Permalink)** across the encyclopedia. Broken links accumulate like digital rust – slowly degrading the structural coherence of the project. Hence, redirects like this one are preserved with the solemnity of a **[time capsule](/Time_capsule)**, even if their utility feels archaic.  

